= News: Coughlin's Sunday Broadcast

Father Coughlin has turned his broadcast into a national political instrument. He attacks bankers, relief administrators, socialists, internationalists, and the White House in the same breath, then offers the NUSJ as the only honest voice left.

The message is contradictory, but it is emotionally precise. In towns where the banks failed and relief checks arrive late, contradiction is not the main thing people hear.

- @answer_airwaves: Answer him on the air.
- @local_clergy: Work through local clergy and party machines.
- @ignore_sermon: Ignore the sermon.

@answer_airwaves
title: Answer him on the air.
subtitle: -1 resources. Slows NUSJ radio growth.
choose-if: resources >= 1
unavailable-subtitle: Not enough resources.
on-arrival: resources -= 1; radio_reach -= 1 if radio_reach > 0; new_deal_legitimacy += 2 if new_deal_legitimacy < 95; old_middle_dnvp -= 2 if old_middle_dnvp > 2

Friendly stations carry a direct rebuttal: the crisis is real, but demagoguery is not relief.

@local_clergy
title: Work through local clergy and party machines.
subtitle: Narrows the damage in Catholic and urban communities.
on-arrival: catholics_spd += 3; old_middle_spd += 2; dnvp_relation -= 2; z_relation += 2

The response is less dramatic than a national speech, but more credible in the places where Coughlin's voice is strongest.

@ignore_sermon
title: Treat it as noise.
subtitle: Saves resources; NUSJ momentum grows.
on-arrival: radio_reach += 1; workers_dnvp += 2; unemployed_dnvp += 2; pro_republic -= 1

The administration has legislation to pass and strikes to settle. Coughlin fills the silence.
